text.tspan: Disparate energy consumption despite similar network activity
Michael Deistler1,2, Pedro J. Gonçalves4 , Jakob H. Macke1,2,3,4

flowRoot.flowPara: 1Excellence Cluster `Machine Learning', Tübingen University 2Comp. Neuroengineering, TUM, Munich,3MPI for Intelligent Systems, Tübingen, 4Center of Advanced European Studies and Research (caesar), Bonn
*These authors contributed equally to this work.

Neural systems can show similar neuronal activity despite disparate parameters such as channel conductances or synaptic strengths. Do disparate solutions with similar activity consume the same amount of energy? Here, we use Bayesian inference to investigate the energy efficiency of different network configurations in a model of the pyloric network in the crab Cancer borealis. We find that a range of circuit configurations in this model can consume vastly different energy despite similar circuit activity. We then analyse this behavior (see full poster).
